{"title":"USA religion fact of the day","link":"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/905100770/0/marginalrevolution~USA-religion-fact-of-the-day.html","date":1727115791000,"content":"<blockquote><p>For the first time in modern American history, young men are now more religious than their female peers. They attend services more often and are more likely to identify as religious.</p>\r\n<p>“We’ve never seen it before,” Ryan Burge, an associate professor of political science at Eastern Illinois University, said of the flip.</p>\r\n<p>Among Generation Z Christians, this dynamic is playing out in a stark way: The men are staying in church, while the women are leaving at a remarkable clip.</p>\r\n<p>Church membership has been dropping in the United States for years. But within Gen Z, almost 40 percent of women now describe themselves as religiously unaffiliated, compared with 34 percent of men, according to a <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.americansurveycenter.org/newsletter/young-women-are-leaving-church-in-unprecedented-numbers/\" target=\"_blank\">survey last year of more than 5,000 Americans</a> by the Survey Center on American Life at the American Enterprise Institute.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Here is <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.nytimes.com/2024/09/23/us/young-men-religion-gen-z.html\" target=\"_blank\">the full story</a> (NYT).</p>\r\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2024/09/usa-fact-of-the-day-10.html\">USA religion fact of the day</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com\">Marginal REVOLUTION</a>.</p>\r\n<img height=\"1\" width=\"1\" src=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/i/905100770/0/marginalrevolution\" />\r\n<div><a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/_/28/905100770/marginalrevolution\"><img height=\"20\